    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-03-19T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-03-19T02:00:00-05:00" n="311"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d311">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/15307: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-03-19T14:00:00+07:00"
                            >March 19, 1944—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 2:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>487. Drumright in telegram from Sian March 18 states report current there that
                    Communists have recently transferred many troops <pb facs="0397" n="383"
                        xml:id="pg_383"/> back to occupied North China from Yenan because of food
                    shortage North Shensi.</p>
                <p>Informed Central Government official states Lin Pai-hsu, chairman Yenan border
                    government, left Yenan March 14 enroute Chungking for discussion Kmt–Communist
                    reactions (Embassy’s 258, February 8, 3 p.m.) and that situation is
                    improving.</p>
                <p>It is reliably reported foreign correspondents will leave Chungking enroute
                    Communist area about April 2 (Embassy’s 456, March 11 [<hi rend="italic"
                    >10</hi>], 4 [<hi rend="italic">7</hi>] p.m.), although no public announcement
                    yet made.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
